sections.content:
A scope graph has scopes (regions of binding), declarations (bindings of names to entities), references (uses of names), and labelled edges between scopes (parent, import, lexical-extension). A reference resolves by traversing edges from the reference's scope outward, collecting visible declarations, applying shadowing and well-formedness conditions along the way.

This design naturally generalizes:

- lexical scoping is parent edges;
- module imports are import edges;
- mixin/inheritance is extension edges;
- type-directed lookup adds query-language predicates over edge labels.

The resolution algorithm becomes a regular path query over labelled graphs, which is well-studied and admits clean caching strategies.
